                    life: [
                        "Manchester is the UK's largest student city outside London — over 100,000 students across the University of Manchester, Manchester Metropolitan University, Royal Northern College of Music, and the University of Salford",
                        "The University of Manchester campus runs along the Oxford Road corridor — claimed to be the busiest bus route in Europe — connecting the city centre, Rusholme's Curry Mile, and Fallowfield's iconic student halls",
                        "Manchester is the birthplace of modern computing — the world's first stored-program computer, the 'Manchester Baby', ran here in 1948, and Alan Turing did his post-war work in the city. The Museum of Science and Industry hosts a working replica",
                        "Football culture is unmatched: Manchester United at Old Trafford and Manchester City at the Etihad Stadium both offer student discounts, and the Manchester Derby is one of world football's biggest rivalries",
                        "Music heritage is part of student life — the Haçienda nightclub, Joy Division, Oasis, The Stone Roses, The Smiths, and the modern Warehouse Project venues all defined Manchester's sound",
                        "The Curry Mile in Rusholme — a half-mile strip of South Asian restaurants — is one of the world's most famous food streets, just a 10-minute walk from the main campus",
                        "Manchester's tram network (Metrolink) is one of the largest in the UK — student travel passes connect the campus to MediaCityUK (the BBC's northern HQ), the Lowry Theatre, and Manchester Airport",
                        "The city is significantly cheaper than London — Manchester's £8,500–£16,000 annual student living cost is around 40–50% lower than central London, a major reason Manchester graduates achieve outstanding return on investment"
                    ],
                    vibes: "Manchester is England's second city of ambition — a former industrial powerhouse that reinvented itself as the cultural, sporting, and intellectual capital of the North. It is the place that gave the world the Industrial Revolution, the suffragette movement (Emmeline Pankhurst's Manchester home is now a museum), the modern computer, and three Nobel Prizes in Physics. Walk down Oxford Road and you pass the John Rylands Library (a Victorian Gothic cathedral of a building), the Whitworth Art Gallery, and the Curry Mile in the same 20 minutes. The city itself is compact, walkable, and famously friendly — the Northern Quarter's independent cafés, Ancoats' loft conversions, and Salford Quays' Imperial War Museum and MediaCity all sit within a tram ride of each other. Football is religion here: Old Trafford and the Etihad bookend the city. And the rain — the running joke of Manchester — has produced more global music (Joy Division, The Smiths, Oasis, The Stone Roses) than any UK city outside London. For students it is a city of energy, low cost, and unmatched cultural depth.",
                    landmarks: "Manchester Cathedral, the John Rylands Library, the Whitworth Art Gallery, the Museum of Science and Industry, Old Trafford Stadium, the Etihad Stadium, the Northern Quarter, MediaCityUK & Salford Quays, the Imperial War Museum North, the Bridgewater Hall, the Manchester Town Hall, the Curry Mile",
