                    vibes: "Edinburgh is the most beautiful capital city in the United Kingdom — a black-stone, candlelit, hill-built town of around 530,000 where every other building is something protected by UNESCO. The city is split between the medieval Old Town (a tangle of vennels and closes climbing up to the Castle, with the Royal Mile running like a spine through it) and the elegant Georgian grid of the New Town below. The university itself is woven into the centre — George Square sits a five-minute walk from the Royal Mile, the Old College is on South Bridge, and the King's Buildings (science and engineering) are a 20-minute bus south. Edinburgh is the city of David Hume, Adam Smith, Sir Walter Scott, Robert Louis Stevenson, Arthur Conan Doyle (who based Sherlock Holmes on his Edinburgh medical professor Joseph Bell), J.K. Rowling (who wrote much of Harry Potter in the Elephant House café here), and the Scottish Enlightenment as a whole. In August the entire city becomes the Fringe — 3,000+ shows over a single month. The weather is brisk, the wind is real, and the light in winter is silver. But the city is compact, walkable, intellectually serious, and unlike anywhere else.",
